Most actions are decided by a single d10 roll.  The most common roll in this game is the \'93skill roll.\'94  This roll is modified by a character\'92s training in the skill as follows:\
\
Untrained: +0\
Proficient: +3\
Experienced: +5\
Master: +6\
\
Difficulty: Difficulty reflects how much understanding and nuance an action requires.  It is largely the chance that a given person might be able to solve or aid in a problem. The standard difficulty range is:\
\
4: Trivial - Easy for anyone, only someone who is untrained can fail.\
6: Ordinary - Easy for someone with training, and anyone with advanced training cannot fail.  This is the common difficulty that most actions have.\
8: Hard - Someone without training is likely to fail, most people with training can figure it out though.\
10: Rare - Someone without advance training is likely to fail, and this problem can stump even experienced practitioners.\
12: Elite - This action is impossible for someone without at least training, and even masters are likely to fail half the time.\
\
Complexity: Complexity reflects how much time and work a specific action requires.  The complexity rating represents how much success players must achieve to complete the test.  When a player succeeds they add their attribute to the success threshold.  A success with a natural roll of a \'9310\'94 means the player contributes double their attribute score.\'94 When the success threshold is equal or larger than the complexity, the characters succeed at the test.\
\
The basic/individual complexity ratings are:\
\
1-2: Immediate\
3-4: Simple\
5-6: Complicated\
\
The group/extended complexity ratings are:\
\
6-9: \
10-12:\
13-15:\
16-18: \
\
\
Every test is either \'93basic\'94 or \'93extended ()\'94  This means that each skill roll either requires a turn, or a longer period of time.  Extended tests have the time between each skill roll listed afterward.  For instance \'93extended (1 minute)\'94 means that each skill roll represents one minute of work.\
\
In general, a failure in a challenge represents a waste of time where no progress is made. If the failed roll is 5 less than the target difficulty then this represents a significant blunder which causes a setback.  Such a roll subtracts 3 from the success threshold.\
